   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604757_1848-06_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener><note>1</note><lb/>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworth Town</placeName><lb/>
                  <date when="1848-06-05">
                     June 5<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>, 1848</date></dateline><lb/>
               <salute>
                  My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StanE1">Lord</persName><lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>So you must permit me to<lb/>
               call you from remembrance<lb/>
               of your kindness to one now<lb/>
               no more whom you honored<lb/>
               by your approbation and<lb/>
               delighted by your goodness</p><lb/>
               <p>Whether your Lordship <choice><orig><unclear>recol<lb/>
                  lect</unclear></orig><reg>recollect</reg></choice>meeting me at my dear<lb/>
                  lost sister <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Wilson</persName>s some<lb/>
               year ago or not, I think you<lb/>
               will for her sake permit this<lb/>
               intrusion and grant me<lb/>
               the favor I am going to ask</p><lb/>
               <p>Allow me to present to<lb/>
               your Lordship a <choice><orig>country<lb/>
                  -man</orig><reg>countryman</reg></choice> of ours for whom she<lb/>
               was much interested and<lb/>
           
<pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604757_1848-06_page02.jpg"/>
               2<lb/>
               for whom all our family as<lb/>
               well as myself are much interested</p><lb/>
            <p>The rev<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SteeT1">Thomas D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Steele</persName> -<lb/>
               He was educated at the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths<lb/>
               town</placeName> school and was one of<lb/>
               my brother <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell E</persName>'s most esteemed<lb/>
               scholars and masters and has<lb/>
               since distinguished himself by<lb/>
               his learning and conduct so<lb/>
               as to obtain a degree of Doctor<lb/>
               of Laws in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Trinity-College_IE">Dublin College</placeName></p><lb/>
            
               <p>Some years ago he was presented<lb/>
                  by the Bishop of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName> with a<lb/>
                  living in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#AU">Australia</placeName> - at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Sydney_AU">Sidney</placeName><lb/>
               - His private letters to himself<lb/>
                  and <add>those</add> to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SteeX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Steele</persName> from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GippG1">Sir George</persName><lb/>
                  &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GippE1">Lady Gipps</persName> tell how much<lb/>
                  they were valued by the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FitzC1">Governer<lb/>
                     of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Sydney_AU"><choice><orig>Sidney</orig><reg>Sydney</reg></choice></placeName></persName> and his <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FitzM1">Lady</persName> - them<lb/>
               selves so valued and beloved<lb/>
                  in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#AU">Australia</placeName> - And the addresses<lb/>
               enclosed will show how much<lb/>
               he was appreciated and<lb/>
               reverenced by his parishioners<lb/>
               
<pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604757_1848-06_page03.jpg"/>
               
               3<lb/>
               and by the inhabitants and<lb/>
                  civil authorities of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Sydney_AU">Sydney</placeName>.</p><lb/>
               <p>With the <unclear>more</unclear> confidence<lb/>
                  I mention <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SteeT1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Steele</persName> to you<lb/>
               my Lord Bishop because I<lb/>
               am assured that his opinions<lb/>
               and practice in Church matters<lb/>
               are in accordance with your<lb/>
               own and equally <unclear>liberal</unclear><lb/>
               steady and sincere in the<lb/>
               true benevolent loving <choice><orig>chari<lb/>
                  table</orig><reg>charitable</reg></choice> spirit of Christianity<lb/>
               <unclear>Respecting</unclear> yet above mere forms</p><lb/>
               <p>I have also another hope<lb/>
                  that this presentation of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SteeT1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Steele</persName><lb/>
               to your Lordship may be pleasing<lb/>
               to you because he has had<lb/>
               the pleasure to be acquainted<lb/>
                  with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StanX2"><choice><abbr>Cap<hi rend="superscript">tn</hi>.</abbr><reg>Captain</reg></choice> Stanley</persName>, and that<lb/>
               his modesty does not empower<lb/>
               me to say so I trust I may say<lb/>
               that he has <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StanX2"><choice><abbr>Cap<hi rend="superscript">tn</hi>.</abbr><reg>Captain</reg></choice> Stanley</persName><unclear>s</unclear> <unclear>upon</unclear><lb/>
               probation and good will</p><lb/>
            <p><persName ref="./Personography.xml#SteeT1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Steele</persName>'s object is, if it<lb/>
               be possible to obtain the means<lb/>
               of<lb/>
               
<pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604757_1848-06_page04.jpg"/>
               
               4<lb/>
               Living and exercising his <choice><orig>func<lb/>
                  -tions</orig><reg>functions</reg></choice> in this country instead<lb/>
               of returning to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Sydney_AU">Sidney</placeName> where<lb/>
               he has been doing hard duty<lb/>
               for upwards of ten years - His<lb/>
               health could hardly stand longer<lb/>
               labor in that situation &amp; climate<lb/>
               - nor could <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SteeX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Steele</persName>s health<lb/>
               or happiness at such a distance<lb/>
               from all her friends be expected<lb/>
               much longer to endure that trial<lb/>
               though her moral courage and<lb/>
               affection have sustained it during<lb/>
               such a protracted period - All<lb/>
               her friends are English - She is the<lb/>
               niece of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JameX1">General <unclear>James</unclear></persName> who served<lb/>
               long in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IN">India</placeName> &amp; is now settled<lb/>
               at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Bath_ENK">Bath</placeName> - The circumstances of<lb/>
               his marriage (permit me to tell<lb/>
               you this <hi rend= "underline">in confidence</hi> as I know<lb/>
               it will ruin him in your opinion<lb/>
               though it might <hi rend= "underline">sink</hi> him with<lb/>
               others) were peculiarly honorable<lb/>
               - he did not conceal the fact of<lb/>
               his humble birth, and the lady<lb/>
               accepted and her friends consented<lb/>
               and the union has consequently been<lb/>
               
<pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604757_1848-06_page05.jpg"/>
               5<lb/>
               eminently happy<lb/>
               I know how a Bishops patronage<lb/>
               and power of assisting must<lb/>
               be limited by the duties of his<lb/>
               Diocese - <del>But</del> I believe there are<lb/>
               13 new benefices created by<lb/>
               S<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PeelR1">R. Peel</persName>s bill - But perhaps<lb/>
               and most probably these have<lb/>
               already been promised or have<lb/>
               half a dozen expectant <choice><orig>Incum<lb/>
                  -bents</orig><reg>Incumbents</reg></choice>. I have more hopes for<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SteeT1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Steele</persName> of his obtaining an<lb/>
               employment for which he<lb/>
               is eminently <unclear>uncontacted</unclear> by<lb/>
               learning morals, &amp; experience<lb/>
               in tracking, the office of<lb/>
               Inspector of Schools.</p><lb/>
               <p>If your Lordship could assist<lb/>
               him in obtaining this <choice><orig>situa<lb/>
                  tion</orig><reg>situation</reg></choice> you would do a public<lb/>
               good - and a private good &amp;<lb/>
               favor which would be most<lb/>
               gratefully felt - </p> <closer>Permit me to<lb/>
               say especially by one who has<lb/>
               
<pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604757_1848-06_page06.jpg"/>
               
               6<lb/>
               the honor to be with the highest<lb/>
               respect, your Lordship's<lb/>
               Obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. humble Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi><lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Mariah Edgeworth</persName><lb/>            
               </closer>

            <closer>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>To</addrLine>
                  <addrLine><persName ref="./Personography.xml#StanE1">The Lord Bishop of Norwich</persName>/</addrLine>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
      </body>
